{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-template-jsx","path":"/creating-a-command-line-interface-program-with-argparse","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<h1 id=\"what-is-argparse\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#what-is-argparse\" aria-label=\"what is argparse permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>What is Argparse?</h1>\n<p><a href=\"https://docs.python.org/3/library/argparse.html\">Argparse</a> is a module that comes pre-installed when you install Python. It allows for the creation of user-friendly command-line interfaces.</p>\n<h2 id=\"creating-a-cli-program-to-find-the-area-of-a-rectangle\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#creating-a-cli-program-to-find-the-area-of-a-rectangle\" aria-label=\"creating a cli program to find the area of a rectangle permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Creating a CLI Program to Find the Area of a Rectangle</h2>\n<img src=\"https://cdn.discordapp.com/attachments/500822770092081163/772226648116035604/026b.PNG\" alt=\"Using argparse to parse two integers\" width=\"550\">\n<p>To start using argparse to recreate the example above, you will need to import the pacakge:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"python\"><pre class=\"language-python\"><code class=\"language-python\"><span class=\"token comment\"># the following code will be contained within a file called area.py</span>\n<span class=\"token keyword\">import</span> argparse</code></pre></div>\n<p>Now we will create a simple method to multiply and return two numbers, like so:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"python\"><pre class=\"language-python\"><code class=\"language-python\"><span class=\"token keyword\">def</span> <span class=\"token function\">area_of_rectangle</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>length<span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> width<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span>\n    <span class=\"token keyword\">return</span> length <span class=\"token operator\">*</span> width</code></pre></div>\n<p>This method will be called when the program is executed. The parameters <code class=\"language-text\">length</code> and <code class=\"language-text\">width</code> will be extracted from the command line arguments.  </p>\n<p>Now we must create a parser to handle the parsing of command-line arguments along with two positional arguments that we want to extract, i.e. the length and the width of the rectangle.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"python\"><pre class=\"language-python\"><code class=\"language-python\">parser <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> argparse<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>ArgumentParser<span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>description<span class=\"token operator\">=</span><span class=\"token string\">'Calculates the area of a rectangle'</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\n\nparser<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>add_argument<span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token string\">'length'</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> default<span class=\"token operator\">=</span><span class=\"token number\">0</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token builtin\">type</span><span class=\"token operator\">=</span><span class=\"token builtin\">int</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token builtin\">help</span><span class=\"token operator\">=</span><span class=\"token string\">'An integer for the length of the rectangle'</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\nparser<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>add_argument<span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token string\">'width'</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> default<span class=\"token operator\">=</span><span class=\"token number\">0</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token builtin\">type</span><span class=\"token operator\">=</span><span class=\"token builtin\">int</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token builtin\">help</span><span class=\"token operator\">=</span><span class=\"token string\">'An integer for the width of the rectangle'</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>We can use the values of these arguments by calling upon <code class=\"language-text\">parser.parse_args()</code>.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"python\"><pre class=\"language-python\"><code class=\"language-python\">args <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> parser<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>parse_args<span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\narea <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> area_of_rectangle<span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>args<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>length<span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> args<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>width<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\n<span class=\"token keyword\">print</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token string\">'The area of your rectangle is: '</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> area<span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token string\">' units squared.'</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>Putting everything together should look like this:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"python\"><pre class=\"language-python\"><code class=\"language-python\"><span class=\"token comment\"># area.py</span>\n<span class=\"token keyword\">import</span> argparse\n\n<span class=\"token keyword\">def</span> <span class=\"token function\">area_of_rectangle</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>length<span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> width<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span>\n    <span class=\"token keyword\">return</span> length <span class=\"token operator\">*</span> width\n\nparser <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> argparse<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>ArgumentParser<span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>description<span class=\"token operator\">=</span><span class=\"token string\">'Calculates the area of a rectangle'</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\n\nparser<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>add_argument<span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token string\">'length'</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> default<span class=\"token operator\">=</span><span class=\"token number\">0</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token builtin\">type</span><span class=\"token operator\">=</span><span class=\"token builtin\">int</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token builtin\">help</span><span class=\"token operator\">=</span><span class=\"token string\">'An integer for the length of the rectangle'</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\nparser<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>add_argument<span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token string\">'width'</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> default<span class=\"token operator\">=</span><span class=\"token number\">0</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token builtin\">type</span><span class=\"token operator\">=</span><span class=\"token builtin\">int</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token builtin\">help</span><span class=\"token operator\">=</span><span class=\"token string\">'An integer for the width of the rectangle'</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\n\nargs <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> parser<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>parse_args<span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\narea <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> area_of_rectangle<span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>args<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>length<span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> args<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>width<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\n<span class=\"token keyword\">print</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token string\">'The area of your rectangle is: '</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> area<span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token string\">' units squared.'</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>Thats about it! Argparse will now parse your command-line agruments for integers to be used in our method. Every parser will have a <code class=\"language-text\">-h</code> optional argument by default; this option will display the help message along with the parser's description.</p>\n<img src=\"https://cdn.discordapp.com/attachments/500822770092081163/772226353188831272/026.PNG\" alt=\"Using -h to display help message\" width=\"550\">","timeToRead":2,"excerpt":"What is Argparse? Argparse is a module that comes pre-installed when you install Python. It allows for the creation of user-friendly command…","frontmatter":{"title":"Creating a Command-Line Interface Program With Argparse","date":"2020-10-31 19:07:19 -0400","categories":["python"],"tags":["Python","cli","args","argparse"],"description":null,"keywords":"Python, cli, args, argparse","author":"Royce Ayroso-Ong","cover":{"childImageSharp":{"fixed":{"base64":"data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABQAAAAPCAYAAADkmO9VAAAACXBIWXMAAAsTAAALEwEAmpwYAAAAZ0lEQVQ4y2Mw5v//n5qYYdRAODbiw60JnxwDPg2GvAhsBKP58BuK04UgzRai//9biUNoM2EIbSJAhgtBWJ/r/3831f//Yx3//4+w/v8/yvb//2i7//+tJSCWDbyXqRopNDFwNOsRjQHOdKSa6R2eoAAAAABJRU5ErkJggg==","width":540,"height":400,"src":"/static/18b0edfdfa96fadbadd7955f1202cbd7/819a5/python.png","srcSet":"/static/18b0edfdfa96fadbadd7955f1202cbd7/819a5/python.png 1x"}}}},"fields":{"slug":"/creating-a-command-line-interface-program-with-argparse","date":"2020-10-31T23:07:19.000Z"}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/creating-a-command-line-interface-program-with-argparse","nexttitle":"JavaScript Array.sort() Method","nextslug":"/javascript-arraysort-method","prevtitle":"Map Interface in Java","prevslug":"/map-interface-in-java","tagList":["abstraction","OOP","Class","java","collection","API","Map","HashMap","LinkedHashMap","TreeMap","Python","cli","args","argparse","javascript","es6","beginner","codenewbie","Primary_key","implementation","Composite_key","language-support","localization","internationalization","linux","file permissions","Project Euler","Algortithms","SQL","database","commands","GO","Datatypes","Variables","Constants","HTML5","Web development","tricks","NumpPy","array","python","NLP","libraries","text processing","go","golang","data-structure","optimization","java 7","Java 8","comparison","mkdir(make-dir) and rmdir(remove-dir command) command","nodejs","backend","frontend","postgres","mac","installation","games",